column1: it was my father and brother.

the reason why i share this........ it was nearly 20 years ago that i tried to have my father charged to protect children still living under the same roof. i was told by the police that one day those kids would come forward and what i'd done was ensure he would be charged down the track. i was devastated and it felt worse than my own abuse to know others were not safe. about ten years later my father died. the damage was done. i promised my brother that if he ever harmed his own children that i would come for him.
last week after eight long years of statements

column1: did you know that 1 out of 3 women and 1 out of 4 men suffer from an abusive relationship in their lifetime? and more that 200
column2: 000 calls are placed to domestic violence hotlines per year? this is a huge problem in our society that is often overlooked. there is two types of abuse
column3: physical and mental (verbal) both can be equally damaging! being in a relationship with these problems the abuser takes away one basic human right and that is the right to be opinionated and angry with them for their treatment to you. no matter how badly they treat you
column4: they believe that your voice shouldn‚Äôt rise and your blood shouldn‚Äôt boil at what they do. the privilege of rage is reserved for them alone. when your anger does jump out of you
column5: when you do realize that you are not treated how you should be and you use your voice to stand up for yourself they are likely to try to jam it back down your throat as quickly as possible and use your anger against you to prove what an irrational person you are. abuse can make you feel like less. it can make you develop physical or emotional reactions to swallowing your anger
column10: and self love issues because you begin to feel like you are the person in the wrong when you are not and with this your partner may use these thing as an excuse to belittle you further or make you feel crazy... this is just the start to my explanation of how damaging a negative relationship like this can be.. i am happy to say that as a survivor from a negative relationship of these sorts i had the opportunity to work with other people who have experienced these situations and together we were able to share our stories and give advice to those going through these situations.. for me
column11: my main piece of advice is don‚Äôt be silent
column13: reach out for help because you deserve better! it is not your fault! i feel honored to be apart of @noellechiodo latest music video ‚Äúyour loves got me blinded‚Äù which touches this subject and definitely hits heart! please take your time to watch her music video and share it so that we can spread awareness to this topic!üíú";;en;;@noellechiodo;;;;0;;rachelhaguefit;Rach ‚ùÅ;;0;False;60;0;0;2819;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/608ae11c2faaab29384783b498799475/5D04FDA9/t51.2885-15/e35/47395118_214342216108463_302955062882535854_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"lets get personal... ‚Ä¢

104020;instagram;2018-12-21 20:10:39;FALSE;an interesting article about the confusion around drinking a #sober family member.

in my experience i think i handled it incorrectly in the beginning because i continued to occasionally drink around my brother after he was sober.  i never kept alcohol in the house when we lived together but looking back it was unnecessary for me even at restaurants and showed my own inability to control my drinking.
the rest of my family members did not stop drinking around him or me and as a result i see them less. it's boring and i have no desire to be around it because it is going to subconsciously impact me.

in treatment no one had family members that stopped drinking around them and many were much younger than me and financially dependent on their families. it was worse for them because they don't have the option to leave and their families will not stop and they get frustrated.

alcohol is addictive and if you continue to drink around your sober family members i would imagine they would eventually relapse or bail on family gatherings. i am happy i supported my brother and didn't drink at events like weddings when others were and got inspired to try sobriety for myself after realizing that i wasn't missing out on anything and life is better without hangovers

column1: 104127;instagram;2018-12-21 17:46:46;FALSE;"i thought i should post less pictures of myself and more of my photography/art but it seems the posts that are most appreciated are the ones where i show myself in times of hardship. interestingly instagrammers also appreciated my own proverb over any of the famous ones i share (i think it's because of the f bomb lol).
cancer is one of those illnesses you can wear like a badge of honour and people can see when you have a bald head and scars
column3: that you are sick. surviving cancer and its treatment makes me feel like a bad-ass mother-fxcker (see i love you: you like a potty mouth
column4: you get a potty-mouth! also people who swear are generally more honest so i am a tried a true lady who doesn't just spew profanities
column5: i enunciate them clearly but i digress).

column1: i've struggled with mental illness and chronic pain for much longer than cancer though (spinal compression fracture at 12
column3: degenerative disc disease and 3 knee surgeries in my 20s). these illnesses are not visible. people assume because i'm a doctor i must be mentally well and i was born with a silver spoon in my mouth which is not true. elderly people talk about chronic pain to me as a doctor and say they wish they were young and pain free like me. i don't tell them how much i hurt. i don't want to take anything away from them. being young and in constant pain is very different though. i have a full lifetime of pain
column4: work and parenting ahead of me. i am still expected to take the stairs (which i do because i know in the long run it helps) and do heavy work around the house. i'm expected to have the stamina to be on my feet all day as most doctors do. i am expected to give my seat to an elderly person on the bus (which i do because we all need to do that!) somedays it's hard to be that person though. somedays
column5: especially now and thank god i have insurance
column6: i can't even walk up a flight of stairs. my point though is not to complain but rather to shed light onto invisible illnesses. we never know what people are going through based on their appearance. we need to talk about these things because when we don't

column1: i have struggled with mental illness and chronic pain for much longer than cancer though (spinal compression fracture at 12
column3: degenerative disc disease and 3 knee surgeries in my 20s). these illnesses are not visible. people assume because i am a doctor i must be mentally well and i was born with a silver spoon in my mouth which is not true. elderly people talk about chronic pain to me as a doctor and say they wish they were young and pain free like me. i do not tell them how much i hurt. i do not want to take anything away from them. being young and in constant pain is very different though. i have a full lifetime of pain
column4: work and parenting ahead of me. i am still expected to take the stairs (which i do because i know in the long run it helps) and do heavy work around the house. i am expected to have the stamina to be on my feet all day as most doctors do. i am expected to give my seat to an elderly person on the bus (which i do because we all need to do that!) somedays it is hard to be that person though. somedays

i‚Äôve gotten hundreds of comments and messages of people sharing their experiences - it‚Äôs overwhelming but i‚Äôm so grateful to be able to use this platform for good. you are all so amazingly strong - whether or not you share - whether or not you report - whether or not you tell a single soul. ‚ú®
your experience is valid. your pain is valid. take all the time you need to heal. you got this. üôèüèº";;en;#FlyLikeAYogi

column2: 2018 marks two years of silence from bartender one. we demand accountability
column3: transparency and action taken by bartender one.

column1: deliberately keeping information on macmillan‚Äôs involvement in bartender one from the community places women and feminized people in danger of experiencing continued and concealed harm.
there is no room for concealing potential risks and there is every obligation to expose people who have created so much harm in our industry and community
please visit our facebook page and circulate because #survivorscantwait

what i know for sure is that speaking your truth is the most powerful tool we have""
this quote really resonated with me at the start of the year. i knew it was time to speak up too. .
it took resistance. and seeing i can't fight it. it took a concussion to see it's time to stand up for myself. to speak up. and more. .
to understand and show that sexual trauma and attachment trauma does not define me. yet it has given me strength and courage. and many lessons. it has been what encouraged and allowed me to open. .
to deepen self love and non-judgement.
pain and purpose are connected. a business coach once told me. .
we co-create our experiences. and i truly feel the new year will show the ""results"" of this. in expected ways. and in unexpected ways. .
what experiences have you co-created? how have they/ will they serve you? and others?

column1: 104291;instagram;2018-12-21 15:31:04;FALSE;"in collaboration with the photographer: praveen kumar (@catch_me_if_u_can_pk)
poem | sara ali (@sara_asfiyali) | the photo cabinet-6 | 'wake up
today you woke up to the world
scrolling down through your facebook feed
syrian child's face soaked in blood and white
then you woke up to a million thoughts
whom you haven't visited ever since
the report card hid under the bedsheets
the greying hair and the dark circles
and you rushed down the old building
squeezed yourself through the busy street
gasped for air in the crowded bus
hit the bed and found your peace.
but then a thought woke you up again
the same feeble voice asked you again
like it did last night and every day before it.

if the song ‚Äúbaby it‚Äôs cold outside‚Äù were a movie scene in modern day it could easily be a horror. the original intention of the song didnt mean to be sexist or sexual harassment. in 1944 & 1946 it actually was just considered romantic for a love interest to not take no as an answer. to pursue no matter what and take what they wanted. however this sentiment and the lyrics haven‚Äôt aged well. no means no means no. this attitude is not cute to replicate in modern day. also while the film that popularized this song neptune‚Äôs daughter made this song more about a woman being concerned about social judgement for her being our late with a man out of wedlock.... the ‚Äúmale love interest‚Äù grabs her roughly several times. pushes her down. pushes himself up against her. interrupts her speaking. it‚Äôs very problematic. at the time though it was a step forward that was celebrated by women because it still was very rare to see women questioning society at all. it‚Äôs complicated but as long as we don‚Äôt glorify the physicality or promote the outdated flirtation tactics that‚Äôs key!

also! i‚Äôve launched a new series with @rosemcgowan called life as lyrics. we will be turning popular songs into movies scenes. we will remove the music and turn the lyrics into straight up dialogue. we want to address the fact that many of us have been lulled into being complicit towards the celebration of rape/violence/greed/selfishness/power abuse by masking the words with catchy beats. we don‚Äôt need this kind of language to have good butt shake and head bob.
to watch the full video and to see a breakdown of what we think about it accompanied by funny animal reactions to the original tune... link in bio!
what do you think of this song? does it have a place in modern playlists? or should it be shelved and/or reimagined?

column1: 104454;instagram;2018-12-21 12:30:33;FALSE;"that feeling at the pit of your stomach
when your love comes to talk to you
all masked behind hurt pain and guilt
i smelled a perfume that reminded me of my love
that is the worse thing i have ever done
i learned a new way of torturing myself
i now just smell the perfume and fall in love all over again
the feeling of drowning in an ocean of sadness and lust
being drowned in that love that i cannot have
i was asked if i would risk my life for the  love of my life
i said yes i would do anything for her
so if you find me dead
it‚Äôs because i drowned in her
falling in love is one of the most dangerous thing a person can experience

my struggles 26 years ago lost and unsure how to deal with my childhood trauma having constant night terrors. i wish i found faith and hope sooner which is why i'm here trying to inspire others to live the best versions of themselves and never let a trauma define who you are. you can be who ever you want..! xo

trying to come out of a panic attack right now. just woke jack up to check it‚Äôs him and asked him to speak to me so i can hear his voice. reminding myself that i‚Äôm on the other side of the bed than what i was in my old reality a minute ago.

column2: it‚Äôs okay and we aren‚Äôt alone. the people who really love you will be there for you through it all even if it takes a long time to tell them.

column1: i‚Äôve been having ptsd therapy now for near 2 years and i thank my therapist and loved ones so much for helping me realise the present when i feel like i‚Äôm being sucked into the past. jack is my rock and so understanding and helpful

i still get flashbacks and especially nightmares (like the one i‚Äôm trying really hard to accept and forget right now). i have tiger balm to smell by my bed to bring me back to the present and have to tell myself what day it is and that it‚Äôs 2018
column3: jack loves you and you‚Äôre getting married next year!!! i‚Äôm a lot better now but it creeps up on you sometimes like tonight.

column1: being a victim of domestic and sexual abuse for so many years has taken its toll on me but i will get through it and smile each day no matter what. i‚Äôm so glad i found my voice and told the people i love and sought the help i needed.
ahhh after writing this down feel like i can breathe a little deeper and slower.
